---
description: Python module size, docstrings, typing, and logging conventions
globs: **/*.py
alwaysApply: false
---

# Module and function size

- Soft limit: any single Python module over ~400 lines must be split
  into a subpackage. Motivating examples from the current tree: the
  819-line pre-split `cursor_view/chat_index.py` became
  `cursor_view/chat_index/` (schema / fingerprint / rebuild / rows /
  index); the 716-line pre-split `cursor_view/extraction/core.py`
  became `cursor_view/extraction/core.py` (thin orchestrator) +
  `cursor_view/extraction/passes/` (one module per pass); the
  629-line pre-split `cursor_view/cache/source_diff.py` became
  `cursor_view/cache/diff/` (types / hashing / cache_state /
  global_db / workspace_db / propagation / engine). Historical
  offenders (pre-refactor `cursor_view/extraction.py` at 377 lines
  and `cursor_view/export_html.py` at 547 lines) are preserved in
  git history; cite the current tree when documenting new splits.
- Soft limit: no function longer than ~100 lines. Break long functions
  into private `_named_helper` functions that describe the pass they
  perform, and keep the top-level function as a short recipe. Recent
  example: `cursor_view/projects/name.py::extract_project_name_from_path`
  (93 lines pre-split) decomposes into `_strip_windows_drive_prefix`,
  `_locate_user_home_dir`, `_choose_project_name_after_home`, and
  `_reject_project_container_names` so the top-level recipe stays
  auditable.

# Docstrings and typing

- Every module starts with a one-line docstring describing its role.
- Every public function has a docstring that explains **why** it
  exists or what invariant it preserves, not what each statement does.
- Prefer typed signatures (`dict[str, Any]`, `list[str]`,
  `pathlib.Path`) over bare `dict` / `list`. `Any` is acceptable for
  heterogeneous JSON pass-through.

# Cross-package imports

Do not import underscore-prefixed helpers across package boundaries.
If a helper is needed by another subpackage, drop the leading
underscore and re-export it through its owning package's
`__init__.py`.

Motivating example: `cursor_view/extraction/core.py` used to import
`_project_from_folder_uri_list`, `_project_from_global_composer_files`,
`_project_from_uri_list`, and `_project_from_workspace_identifier`
straight out of `cursor_view/projects/inference.py`. The
structure-cleanup plan dropped the leading underscores and
re-exported them through `cursor_view.projects` as
`project_from_folder_uri_list` / `project_from_global_composer_files`
/ etc., so `extraction/passes/global_composers.py` and
`extraction/passes/uri_fallbacks.py` now import the public aliases.
Underscore-prefixed helpers are a signal to readers that the name is
package-private; crossing that boundary hides a de-facto public API.

# Import-time side effects

Module-load must be free of external side effects: no filesystem
sweeps, no network, no Flask app construction, no cache-directory
mutation. Side-effecting work belongs inside a `main()` /
`run_*()` function that the CLI or test harness calls explicitly.
Merely importing a module to read a symbol out of it must never
touch the user's disk or process state.

Motivating example: the pre-refactor `cursor_view/terminal.py` ran
`cleanup_orphan_temp_files()` and `app = create_app()` at the top
level, so anything that imported the module for `run_server`'s
signature (including introspection tools) would trigger a
cache-directory sweep and Flask construction as a side effect.
(Filed as bug #12 in the structure-cleanup plan; the fix is deferred
to the follow-up bug-fix plan, but new code must not repeat the
pattern.)

# Logging

Use lazy `%`-style logging, not f-strings, inside
`logger.debug/info/warning/error`. f-strings are evaluated even when
the log level is disabled; lazy formatting defers the work.

```python
# Wrong
logger.info(f"Loaded {count} chats")
# Right
logger.info("Loaded %s chats", count)
```
